title: Hold Down Bar - Medium, low profile tip

description.text:
With my Shapeoko 3, I wanted a version of these hold downs that didn't go as high above the material, as they interfere with my dust collection shoe. This is my attempt to solve that problem. If there is interest, I'll try to repeat the remix with the short and long versions of the hold-down bar. I usually use the medium one, so I don't need the others. EDIT:
As commented on in the comments section, the original design de-laminated after about a year of use. I've re-designed for my purposes. This new one is smaller, using less plastic, but doesn't have as much of a lip to delaminate (I believe). These in PLA have a slight flex in them as well, which works well for me. I position properly, and flex until the flat part is just about flat, and I feel I have enough pressure. Check back in a year to see if this one also fails on me. Whenever I really need a strong hold-down, I use the original ones I derived this design from.

This is my first attempt at a remix, so who knows if I'm doing it right.  I used Fusion 360 to import the original and cut away part, then exported to stl.  I'm not yet sure how to get to the .dwg file in Fusion, but I'll add it when I do.
Oddly, when importing the original .dwg into Fusion 360, it became 10x too large, so I had to scale it down.  Then I rotated it to the proper orientation for printing and exported it as stl.
The second design (now listed as the first file) was an almost complete re-build in Fusion 360.  I copied out the tapers from the original designs so that the teeth match properly.  Works great for me.. hope you have the same luck.  Perhaps someday I'll add images.

comments.text:
I'm not sure how you are using this for clamping, but the spot you should be clamping with the bevel on the bottom where the angle starts... not on the very end / nose of the bar. I'm not sure that in as understandable as it could be so I've annotated with arrows where the clamp point is:
https://goo.gl/photos/c7wxdcdMHSsHep7K6
comments.author: DasWookie

comments.text: Yes, indeed with the thicker ones, I clamp where you suggest (not on the tip, but on the slight bend), and position as you suggest (your comments in your design were very helpful, thanks!)  I have to admit this design was mostly me playing with Fusion 360 and also with thingiverse.  As such, USERS BEWARE!  DasWookie's comments are all valid.  That said, I've used these a couple of times now, and feel there is plenty of holding power for my needs.  I do only lightweight work on wood so far, so I expect the stresses are much smaller than what other might need.  Perhaps I'll try my hand again at Fusion 360 to see if I can design some goose-neck style clamps for 3d-printing.
comments.author: DasWookie

comments.text: After looking at the goose neck design, I wondered if just making the original clamps thinner would be reasonable?  What were your guidelines on keeping them as thick as they are?  I suppose there might be a bit of flex in them and some reduced clamping pressure, but even with my small tips, I feel like if I tighten enough to bend the tips, that I will pull the threaded inserts out of the MDF table.  Definitely they dent the baltic birch plywood I'm working with.  That is, there might be more significant issues with clamping pressure than the position of the bar.  I (sort of) see what I've designed as a very thin goose neck.  (Though I do like the image you sent better as it also keeps the back of the bar lower.)

description.text: This replacement for the Deltaprintr extruder's lower section provides a guide for filament so it can't push out sideways when there's a little resistance. It helps immensely for printing soft filaments, like flex PLA or wood. Inspired by Valentin's replacement for my original replacement extruder floor. This was modeled from the ground up in (freely-available) OpenSCAD and pushes a little further into the gear area than Valentin's version. The OpenSCAD source file is included if you need to tweak tolerances for your printer. Everything's commented, you should be able to figure out which numbers to tweak. When assembling, try to push the ridge with the filament hole up as close to the bearing & gear as possible while tightening the screws. You really want it pushing up there so the filament doesn't have any wiggle room between the gear and the filament guide. If you use the "with tube" version, you'll need to insert a short (~13mm or 1/2") section of 4mm PTFE tubing into the hole above the push fitting. It'll stick up into the V between the drive gear and the pinch bearing. You'll need to use a knife to whittle the tube into a point that fits between the two surfaces as closely as possible. Whittle and test fit, whittle and test fit. TIP: You can cut a piece from your bowden tube for this; it's plenty long enough. Updates 2017.05.25 - Adds teflon tube option. Tightens up gaps around drive gear.

So I purchased an Arducopter Pre-assembled and tested, Something I rarely do.  Maybe it was a subconscious action then, that within a week I had smashed it into the ground?
Now I am designing and rebuilding it, testing and learning and really enjoying it. 
Some pieces survived and I had initially thought to design things as a replacement/upgrade. Now I think that would be silly to tell people to "Print these, and buy these 'special' parts", so I am making the attempt to make this frame fully DIY...
I haven't really been documenting the process, but initially it seemed there would be a slight weight savings in the carbon fiber/ABS parts vs the stock arducopter aluminum/acrylic parts. 
Maybe some different construction methods could be used to increase savings?
This is very much a work in progress, but thought I'd get the idea out in order get some feedback and enable collaboration.

The goal:
Get some carbon fiber shafts.. Got mine at walmart for $3 a shaft(29 inch, ~8mm dia. arrow shafts), I estimate it will take 6-8 of these, depending on desired frame size..
Print parts.
Use 3mm hardware to assemble nuts and bolts
Frame complete. Add electronics..
*update 08/19/2011:
Added the concept pieces I am currently using for the pyramid cage, as well as another mock-up image, this time with some electronics mounting ideas. I'm going to try to throw the minimal amount of electronics on and get a test flight tonight.. Hopefully the first won't coincide with the last!

I am a student in Israel Ra'anana at the age of 15. I use Inventor and Cura to design and print. a wheel
The wheel is divided into 8 sections in which one is missing in order to Play the music right. On the base are mounted 3 stripes at the thickness of 2, 3 and 4 mm, with each plaing a diffarent note. Connecting the handle is done with friction using an extending hexagon on the handle and an inword going hexagon (slightly larger) in the wheel itself. Although the original device is made on metal, building it out of pure platic did produce a sound, yet not as "clean". The base and the wheel both have a hole in them so it is easy and clear how to put it together :)

Designing this was not a simple task, the idea hit me in a class in school and I just drew it, drew whatever came to mind, Later that day I went home and straight away got on the computer and started designing.
Almost every part failed at first, the handle broke the moment I touched it... so I remade it.
the wheel did not fit at all, so I remade it.

They somehow made it though everything and refuse to break, the wheel had to go in "the wrong" way because I was not using metal and I really shouldn't have pushed those thin parts down, Gravity already got that one covered, so I just push them upwards. title: Bulldog Lite Extruder, eBay E3D clone heatsink and Heatbed fan mount

description.text:
Frustrated with my Bulldog Lite extruder I decided to expand on the heatsink fan mount I designed. The Extruder mount comes in two flavours. Either 2 hole mounted, onto the Ooznest carriage, or onto the stock Rework carriage with 4 holes. Included is a STL for a fan mount for an eBay E3D style heatsink. This is practically identical to the heatsink fan mount I've published as a standalone. This one has just been shaved a mm shorter, so the fan is closer to the heatsink. This means if you use a 6mm or 7mm deep 30mm cooling fan, then the entire heatsink cooler will rotate and fit neatly under the extruder mount. Also included is a heatbed fan mount that duplicates spacing of the stock extruder mount, ie the one that comes with it. This means any heatbed cooling solution you are currently using should simply just bolt on without fiddlying around. PLEASE NOTE.
The eBay E3D style heatsink clone is different to a proper E3D heatsink. You can look at my photo and just count the number of fins. Whats next?
An add-on for a inductive sensor pickup

Notes: Bulldog_lite_extruder_v7_mount* Okay, I suggest printing both bulldog_lite_extruder_v7_mount* orientated as they are. It does mean that quite possibly a lot of support is needed. But printing this way the layers will be in line with the extruder and I think make it a lot stronger.
The shafts in these parts are 3mm and the nut traps fit the 3mm nuts. You will most likely need to tidy up with a 3mm drill bit. Depending of the quality of your print, you might need to heat the nuts to get them to fit into the nut traps. Do not be tempted to rush it by overheating the nuts.

title: Qubd twoup z wobble fix, z rod stabilizer

description.text:
This is a part I made to reduce the z wobble i witness when watching the z screw turn. I was able to see the screw moving left and right as it spun, and it affected my prints in a bad way. Designed around a brass flange bearing I bought from Home Depot that has an inside diameter matching the twoup z-screw. These are self lubricating and cost around 3 - 4 dollars. http://www.homedepot.com/p/Crown-Bolt-3-8-in-x-5-8-in-x-1-in-Bronze-Flange-Bearing-57738/203537359. The bearing holder is designed to mount onto the base, using 3 m3 16mm screws that mount onto the Z motor through the base. this will hold the brass bearing steady even if your motor axle isn't quite aligned with the z screw.
This whole thing is used in conjunction with the hirth coupler (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:397553), and a piece of thick foam pad was used and placed in betweenfor some give. This combination works really well to curb my z wobble.

Ben Jackson's Top Guide was an essential addition to my Accessible Wade's Extruder as the filament kept falling off the hobbed bolt when it was tugged to one side.  His Top Guide ensures that no matter what the angle of the incoming filament, it remains vertically centered above the hobbled bolt before it enters the extruder.
My (extremely) minor improvement is the addition of a locking clip that holds it in place when screwed in. The original top guide tends to flip along the axis of the bolt a bit as it is only held in place on one side, and if it moves, it defeats the purpose of the item.

There's one STL for the larger 3mm filament and the smaller 1.75mm filament. The larger one is probably fine for both uses, but they're both there just in case. Print, apply pressure in the direction of the gear while inserting bolt, thread filament through hole.
The inserted bolt applies pressure against the clip preventing the top guide from lifting up during the filament feed.

description.text:
This is a work in progress of creating a new opensource PCR machine that is faster and more robust in some ways than commercial machines for around 50-100 times cheaper. It uses 8mm diameter for the rails, the step motor is attached with m4 screws and all other screws are m3. It will be using 3 water baths instead of peltier for heating/cooling. The design will later include heated lid although with the added speed plus allowing the test tubes to be submerged in water the heated lid might not be necessary as condensation might not have time to happen. It is designed to work with 96 well holders and they can be stacked 3-4 times so it should be able to PCR on a few hundred 0.2ml tubes in 20-30minutes. All electronics will be using parts available for 3d printing and Arduino so everything can be sourced locally with no single hard to purchase part. It can be extended to use 2-4 temperature zones. One extra added benefit is that it will use up to 80% less electricity than peltier baser PCR machines. files are also available on git, including arduino source

description.text:
Being disabled should not mean being disadvantaged, and no one should be left behind as technology progresses. Losing an arm or the use of a hand today could make using a smartphone difficult. This strap-on arm allows one-handed phone operation as part of the #AssistiveTech challenge. Parts needed:
  • Print one of each file (files labelled “b”, e.g. 1b and 4b are options). Refer to attached “Parts Catalog” screen shot.
  • 8 x M3*12mm screws
  • 2 x M3*6mm OR 8mm screws
  • 1 x M4*30mm bolt & nut
  • 4 x short self-tapping screws
  • 1 x 1/2” electrical trunking
  • 2 rubber bands
  • 1 x M5*40mm bolt & nut
  • 1 x M5*60mm bolt & nut
  • 1 x length of 10mm strap
    • Assembly:
  • Run strap through Base unit loops. Secure ends with dead knots (I might add a self-locking clip later)
  • Mount Base Socket to Base unit, using 4 M3*12mm screws. Note, these are designed to enter at an angle toward the underside of the socket.
  • Insert Ball Joint.
  • Install M4*30mm bolt through Lock Handle, fasten with the nut. Screw it into the Socket base
  • Connect Phone Assembly Connector to the Phone Assembly Swivel with a M5*40mm bolt and nut. Fasten to provide some resistance.
  • Add Phone Holder Base to that assembly with M5*60mm bolt and nut. Fasten to provide some resistance.
  • Install Phone Back Support using 2 M3*6mm or 8mm screws.
  • Slot both Phone Grips through assembly. Install 4 M3*12mm screws to all four ends - Do not install fully, the protrusion acts as a brake and to loop the rubber bands (next step).
  • Connect the opposite ends of both Phone Grips with a rubber band each, double loop if required to provide good resistance when both grips are pulled apart. These hold the phone in place.
  • Measure a length of electrical trunking to connect both Base and Phone assemblies. This simulates a forearm. Cut TWO same lengths. Secure in the hexagon ports with self-tapping screws.
  • Wear the whole unit, adjust to a comfortable viewing angle, lock the arm with the Lock Handle. Install phone.
    • Video here: https://youtu.be/gigb-_6cvnM ** Credit to FunbieStudios for ball & socket joint. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:70366

title: Tie Bomber for Casual X-Wing Gaming

description.text:
This is a Tie bomber model scaled for casual use in the X-Wing miniatures game. Given the new munitions options, it seemed timely!
The model is a derivative of NenZilla's model, which in turn is remixed from ProCoPrint3D's unprintable model. I rescaled to X-Wing miniatures gaming size, bolstered the connection between the body and the fins, and added the connector to the bottom to accept a standard X-Wing peg. The connector actually fits around the peg stem to help keep the model on the base.
The raft is just a little 0.3mm bit that fits nicely underneath to provide a base for supports.
Note: The "angled" version of the model is simply to create a better Thingiverse image: you don't really need it.

Made in Modo. This needs no supports although with the large curved holes it can be a challenge for printing overhang but it worked fine on my Rep 2. I did make minor tweaks to the model based on the print in the photo; increased the base, increased the upper curve on the holes and increased the resolution. Probably best to print out at a large size because of the thickness of the top spheres. Turning it into a table lamp or nightlight:
Materials:
  • two prong led light socket (Home Depot)
  • 12 V transformer (The Source or Home Depot)
  • on/off switch (Home Depot)
  • any wires for lengthening the distance from the light to the wall plug
  • 12V led light (in this case there are two led lights as part of the bulb - Home Depot)
    • Get a 12 V transformer, - one option is from The Source (Radio Shack) and another from Home Depot's light department (used for led lights). Purchased a 12V led light, the one in the picture is the perfect size for the default size of the print, make sure it is the right size to just fit the first level hole of the print. I brought in the light socket and wires from the back and tied it with a half hitch to one of the bottom legs of the print (see the images) - that is at the back so if you arrange it right you won't see that. Wired the 12V transformer to a two prong light socket, (see images) and then hot glued the outer rim of the led light and quickly pushed it up into the light house from below into the the first level hole to affix it. I also added an on/off switch, which can be purchased in the same area as the two prong light socket at Home Depot. Update: don't use hot glue if you leave the light on for any length of time. The led lights get hotter than I thought they would and it melts the hot glue. I will have to rethink this problem. ...I have now created a led light stand for this purpose: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:602016
